### Records in C#

Records are reference types (or value types with `record struct`) that provide built-in value equality, immutability, and concise syntax for data-centric types. Introduced in C# 9.

### Declaring Records

```csharp
// Positional record (primary constructor syntax)
public record Person(string Name, int Age);

// Equivalent nominal record
public record Person
{
    public string Name { get; init; }
    public int Age { get; init; }
}
```

### Record Features

```csharp
var person1 = new Person("Alice", 30);
var person2 = new Person("Alice", 30);

// Value equality
Console.WriteLine(person1 == person2);  // True
Console.WriteLine(person1.Equals(person2));  // True

// ToString
Console.WriteLine(person1);  // "Person { Name = Alice, Age = 30 }"

// Non-destructive mutation (with expression)
var olderAlice = person1 with { Age = 31 };

// Deconstruction
var (name, age) = person1;
Console.WriteLine($"{name}, {age}");
```

### Record Structs (C# 10+)

```csharp
// Value type record
public readonly record struct Point(double X, double Y);

// Mutable record struct
public record struct Vector3(float X, float Y, float Z);
```

### Record Methods

Records auto-generate:

| Member | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| `Equals()` | Value-based equality |
| `GetHashCode()` | Hash based on all properties |
| `ToString()` | Formatted output with property names |
| `==` / `!=` | Value equality operators |
| `Deconstruct` | Deconstructor for positional records |
| `Clone` | Protected copy constructor for `with` |

### Records with Custom Members

```csharp
public record Student
{
    public string Name { get; init; }
    public int Grade { get; init; }

    // Computed property
    public bool IsPassing => Grade >= 60;

    // Custom method
    public string GetReport() => $"{Name}: {Grade} ({(IsPassing ? "Pass" : "Fail")})";
}

// Usage
var student = new Student { Name = "Bob", Grade = 85 };
Console.WriteLine(student.GetReport());
```

### Records and Inheritance

```csharp
public record Person(string Name, int Age);
public record Employee(string Name, int Age, string Company) : Person(Name, Age);

var emp = new Employee("Alice", 30, "Microsoft");
Console.WriteLine(emp);  // "Employee { Name = Alice, Age = 30, Company = Microsoft }"
```

### Sealed Records

```csharp
public sealed record Point(int X, int Y);
// Cannot derive from Point
```

### Record vs Class

| Aspect | Record | Class |
|--------|--------|-------|
| Equality | Value-based | Reference-based by default |
| Immutability | Init-only by default | Mutable by default |
| Syntax | Concise for data | General purpose |
| Use case | DTOs, models, values | Business logic, services |
| ToString | Auto-generated | Type name only |
| `with` expression | Supported | Not supported |
| Deconstruction | Supported for positional | Manual implementation |

> **Key Point:** Records are ideal for data transfer objects (DTOs), API models, and value objects. They provide value equality, immutability, and concise declaration. Use `with` expressions for non-destructive mutation. Use `record struct` for value-type records.

### JSON Serialization

```csharp
var json = JsonSerializer.Serialize(new Person("Alice", 30));
var person = JsonSerializer.Deserialize<Person>(json);
```

### Records with Required Properties (C# 11+)

```csharp
public record Product
{
    public required string Name { get; init; }
    public required decimal Price { get; init; }
}

codeExample:
using System;

public record OrderItem(string Product, int Quantity, decimal Price)
{
    public decimal Total => Quantity * Price;
}

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        var item1 = new OrderItem("Laptop", 1, 999.99m);
        var item2 = item1 with { Quantity = 2 };  // Non-destructive mutation

        Console.WriteLine(item1);
        Console.WriteLine($"Total: {item1.Total:C}");
        Console.WriteLine($"Item2: {item2}");

        // Value equality
        var item3 = new OrderItem("Laptop", 1, 999.99m);
        Console.WriteLine($"Equal: {item1 == item3}");  // True
    }
}
